{"author":"Joe Oakhart","data":{"fields":{"description":"## Context\nStamp denormalized author identity on every mutating event (git-style: a name and\nan email travel *in* the event), plus an OPTIONAL `author_id` referencing an\n`identity` ticket (from ddbe), at rebar's locked write seam — without breaking\nreplay of events written before this change. This is the attribution substrate the\nauthorship attestation (bde5) and enforcement (3183) build on.\n\n## Why\nAuthorship certification needs every event to record who wrote it in a form that\nsurvives replication and compaction (denormalized, not a lookup). An optional\n`author_id` links to the rich `identity` entity when one is resolvable, while the\ndenormalized name/email keep working when it is not (identity is opt-in).\n\n## What\n### 1. Shared git-config primitive + attribution helper (`src/rebar/_commands/_seam.py`)\n- Extract a `_git_config(key: str, fallback: str = \"\") -> str` primitive from the\n  existing `author()` helper (which shells `git config user.name`); reimplement\n  `author()` on top of it and add `author_email()` = `_git_config(\"user.email\", \"\")`.\n  Both strip output and return the fallback on unset / OSError / non-zero — NEVER\n  raise. (Consolidates the copy-paste `author()` clone flagged in review; do NOT\n  also refactor the unrelated clones in compact.py/init.py — out of scope.)\n- Add `attribution_fields(repo_root=None) -> dict` returning\n  `{\"author_email\": author_email()}` plus `{\"author_id\": <id>}` ONLY when\n  `rebar._commands.identity.resolve_current_identity(repo_root=repo_root)` is not\n  None (its real signature is keyword-only `resolve_current_identity(*, repo_root=None)`\n  per ddbe's implementation — verified, not the bare `()` the ddbe AC text abbreviated).\n  MEMOIZE per resolved `repo_root` for the process lifetime (module-level dict), so a\n  batch of N writes does at most ONE git call + ONE ticket scan, not N.\n\n### 2. Stamp at the write seam(s)\n- `append_event`: merge `attribution_fields(repo_root)` into the envelope next to the\n  existing `\"author\"` (name) key — `\"author_email\"` always; `\"author_id\"` present only\n  when resolved. The batch-sink path composes through the SAME block, so buffered\n  events are byte-identical (add BEFORE the sink branch).\n- `src/rebar/_commands/delete.py` bypasses `append_event` and builds envelopes\n  directly in `_write_unlink` (~line 112) and `_write_event` (~line 202), stamping\n  STATUS(deleted)/ARCHIVED/UNLINK events. Mirror the same `attribution_fields()` merge\n  there so deletion/archival events are attributed too (otherwise the \"every event\"\n  AC has a hole). These take a precomputed `author` name already; add the email/id\n  fields from the shared helper.\n\n### 3. Replay back-compat (reducer surfaces attribution PRESENT-ONLY)\nSurface the fields **present-only** (mirrors `source_*`): set `state[\"author_email\"]`\n/ `state[\"author_id\"]` ONLY when the event carries them, at each processor that\nalready stamps `author` — the verified sites are `process_create`\n(_processors.py:59), `process_comment` (:248), `process_revert` (:374), and\n`process_signature` (:494). (`process_edit`/`process_status` do NOT stamp author and\nare NOT edited.) Consequences:\n- An event written BEFORE this change (no `author_email`/`author_id`) reduces to\n  **byte-identical** compiled state — no new keys — so \"same state\" holds exactly and\n  nothing can crash on a missing key.\n- A new event surfaces `author_email` always and `author_id` when resolved, so bde5\n  can read `author_id` off compiled state.\n- SNAPSHOT: `process_snapshot` restores compiled_state verbatim, so snapshots written\n  after this change naturally carry the fields — additive and harmless (an older\n  reducer ignores unknown state keys); no special handling needed.\n\n## Scope\nIn: the `_git_config`/`author_email`/`attribution_fields` helpers + cache, the\nappend_event + delete.py stamping, the reducer present-only surfacing, and the\nback-compat + caching tests. Out: signing/verifying authorship (bde5), key lifecycle\n(e165), enforcement (3183). `author_id` is populated but NOT verified or required here.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] Every mutating event's envelope carries `author` (name) AND `author_email`; a\n  test writes via TWO different commands (`create` and `comment`) and asserts BOTH raw\n  stored event JSONs contain `author_email` (proving it is the shared seam, not\n  per-command). A deletion event (via `delete.py`) likewise carries `author_email`.\n- [ ] When a current identity is resolved (`rebar identity use <id>`), a write carries\n  `author_id == <id>` in the raw event AND the reduced state surfaces\n  `author_id`/`author_email`; when NO identity resolves, the `author_id` key is ABSENT\n  from both the raw event and the reduced state (test both branches).\n- [ ] Back-compat: a hand-authored event stream WITHOUT `author_email`/`author_id`\n  reduces without error to compiled state that has NEITHER key (byte-identical to\n  pre-change), asserted by reducing a synthetic pre-change event and diffing the dict.\n- [ ] `author_email()` returns `\"\"` (never raises) when `git config user.email` is\n  unset or the git call fails — tested by forcing the subprocess to error.\n- [ ] Caching: N sequential writes in one process resolve the identity/email at most\n  once — asserted by monkeypatching `resolve_current_identity` (or the git-email call)\n  with a call-counter and doing several writes, expecting count <= 1.\n\n## file_impact\n- `src/rebar/_commands/_seam.py` (_git_config + author_email + attribution_fields + cache + append_event stamping)\n- `src/rebar/_commands/delete.py` (stamp attribution on the direct-envelope deletion/unlink events)\n- `src/rebar/reducer/_processors.py` (present-only surfacing at the 4 author-stamping processors)"}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1783820961448989001,"uuid":"ff631cee-521e-436e-8a50-c8625c835304"}